					<description><![CDATA[<p>The way emergency services operate could change in the United States as drone-maker BRINC raises $125 million. The funding round led by Motorola Solutions will provide funding for BRINC to</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/brinc-raises-125-million-for-911-response-drones/" data-wpel-link="internal">BRINC Raises $125 Million To Give U.S. Police &amp; Fire Stations 911 Response Drones</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The way emergency services operate could change in the United States as drone-maker BRINC raises $125 million. The </span><a href="https://x.com/BrincDrones/status/2077114082457522668" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding round</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> led by Motorola Solutions will provide funding for BRINC to place autonomous 911 response drones on the roof of every police and fire station in the United States. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded in 2019 by Blake Resnick, now 26, the Seattle-based startup is turning “Drone as a First Responder” (DFR) programs into a nationwide reality. Backed by industry giants like Index Ventures and OpenAI’s Sam Altman, the company is scaling up fast.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">BRINC is Scaling American Manufacturing</span></h2>
<div id="attachment_203585" style="width: 810px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203585" class="size-full wp-image-203585" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/BRINC-drones.jpg" alt="The BRINC autonomous drone system featuring an outdoor response aircraft deploying directly from its dedicated robotic charging station." width="800" height="418" /><p id="caption-attachment-203585" class="wp-caption-text">BRINC Drones and Automated Rooftop</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Following the $125 million BRINC funding round, the startup has now raised more than $280 million in total capital. The latest capital injection will help BRINC expand its drone manufacturing capacity, hire top-tier talent and bring new hardware to market. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Participating in this round alongside Motorola are existing investors like Index Ventures and Figma founder Dylan Field. To support this rapid scaling, BRINC is moving its headquarters into the West Canal Yards in Seattle’s Queen Anne neighborhood. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This 60,000-square-foot facility offers three times the production space of their current factory. BRINC expects to grow its workforce from 187 employees to more than 250 by the time the facility opens, ensuring they can meet the soaring demand.</span></p>
<p><b><i>More Updates: </i></b><a href="https://ventureburn.com/lumin-digital-raises-115m-to-drive-ai-banking/" data-wpel-link="internal"><b><i>Lumin Digital Raises $115M Valuation To Drive AI Banking</i></b></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Integrating Drones into 911 Dispatch</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">BRINC does more than build drones. They are working on creating an emergency response network that is interconnected. This is one of the major reasons for their close partnership with Motorola Solutions. It helps the startup integrate its drones into modern 911 call systems.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">When you place an emergency call, a BRINC drone can launch automatically from its rooftop station. A police officer can also manually deploy a drone instantly using their standard Motorola hand-held radio. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This seamless connection ensures response times are as quick as possible. The company’s impressive lineup features the Lemur 2 for indoor SWAT operations, the Responder for quick dispatch, and the Guardian.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The Guardian is a large, Starlink-connected drone built to replace police helicopters. These tools arrive on the scene minutes before ground crews, delivering vital live-streamed video and life-saving medical supplies.</span></p>
<p><b><i>More Updates: </i></b><a href="https://ventureburn.com/rime-raises-24m-series-a-enterprise-voice-ai/" data-wpel-link="internal"><b><i>Rime Raises $24M for Enterprise-Ready Speech-To-Speech AI Models</i></b></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Capitalizing on Domestic Market Shifts</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">BRINC is capitalizing on a major regulatory shift. The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) block on foreign drones locked out the likes of DJI from the U.S. public safety market. As a result, emergency departments are looking for high-quality, domestic alternatives.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Since BRINC builds all of its drones entirely in the U.S., they are completely immune to import bans. This regulatory tailwind helped BRINC triple its revenue in 2025. It has also quadrupled its active 911 response contracts this year.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The startup has also welcomed prominent new customers like the Los Angeles Fire Department and the St. Louis Police Department. Currently, over 900 emergency agencies utilize BRINC’s technology. With approximately 80,000 public safety stations across the U.S., BRINC has a massive market to conquer.</span></p>
<p><b><i>More Updates: </i></b><a href="https://ventureburn.com/daniel-ek-neko-health-raises-700-million-preventive-tech/" data-wpel-link="internal"><b><i>Daniel Ek’s Neko Health Raises $700M For Preventive Health Tech</i></b></a></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/brinc-raises-125-million-for-911-response-drones/" data-wpel-link="internal">BRINC Raises $125 Million To Give U.S. Police &amp; Fire Stations 911 Response Drones</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
